Estranhos and João Canijo’s Fantasia Lusitana -- tAbout the Authors -- tIndex of Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt a time when migration is mostly discussed in terms of “conflict” and “crisis”, it is decidedly important to acknowledge the discursive traditions, narrative patterns, and conceptual categories that continue to inform how migration is represented, analyzed and theorized in contemporary Europe. This volume focuses on the potential of artistic and critical practices to challenge hegemonic framings of migration and embrace the ambivalence inherent in migration as a conflictual, often violent, yet also liberating uprooting. By placing special emphasis on “peripheral” perspectives and subject positions, the volume provides new insights into topics such as belonging and exclusion, the “migrant crisis”, and memory. By bringing into dialogue creative practices and academic discourses, it explores how new modes of seeing and theorizing may emerge through experiences and representations of migration. Situated within the field of literary and cultural studies, it complements historical and social analyses in the emerging interdisciplinary field of migration studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aArts.  aFilm.  aLiterature.  aMigration.1 aBayraktar, Nilgun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalafate Ribeiro, Margarida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCristina Cachola, Ana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarraio, Júlia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJuvonen, Annimari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJuvonen,